{"title_page": "Katie Skelly", "text_new": "{{short description|Cartoonist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolor       = \n| name          =\n| image         = KatieSkelly2019SPX.png\n| imagesize     =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Skelly speaking at the [[Small Press Expo]] in 2019\n| birth_date    = February 5, 1985\n| birth_place   = [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[comics artist]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n| website       =\n}}\n'''Katie Skelly''' is an American [[comics artist]] and illustrator. She is best known for her [[graphic novels]] ''My Pretty Vampire'', ''Operation Margarine'' and ''Nurse Nurse''.\n\n==Biography==\nKatie Skelly was born in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Her father's side of the family operated a newsstand in downtown Bethlehem and he brought her comics from the stand to read. She began drawing her own comics in high school, and after graduating from college, Skelly began her science fiction-themed, ''[[Barbarella (comics)|Barbarella]]''-inspired series ''Nurse, Nurse''. She received a B. A. in Art History from [[Syracuse University]] and followed it with graduate coursework at [[City College of New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcj.com/ugly-is-good-an-interview-with-katie-skelly/|title=\"Ugly Is Good\": An Interview with Katie Skelly|last=Mautner|first=Chris|work=[[The Comics Journal]]|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\nIn 2017 [[Fantagraphics Books]] published Skelly's first hardcover graphic novel ''My Pretty Vampire'', notable for its \"dramatic colors\" and \"sense of mercurial motion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/it-s-feeding-time-for-my-pretty-vampire-in-this-exclusi-1798265877/|title=It\u2019s feeding time for My Pretty Vampire in this exclusive preview|last=Sava|first=Oliver|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Inspired by the Italian horror films of [[Dario Argento]] and the early work of comics illustrator [[Jean-Claude Forest]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/my-pretty-vampire-katie-skelly-interview/|title=Katie Skelly Combines Cute Art with Sexy Horror in My Pretty Vampire|last=Lorah|first=Michael C.|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=August 9, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> the story follows a young vampire who escapes captivity by her brother to discover herself through surreal, sensual and often violent adventures in the modern world.\n\nSkelly's other works include ''Operation Margarine'' (2014, [[Adhouse Books]]), for which she was awarded the inaugural Emerging Artist Prize at the [[Cartoon Crossroads Columbus]] Festival in 2015;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartooncrossroadscolumbus.com/guest/2017/Katie%20Skelly|title=Katie Skelly: CXC 2017 Guest Illustrator|last=|first=|work=cartooncrossroadscolumbus.com|date=2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> ''The Agency'' (2018, [[Fantagraphics Books|Fantagraphics]] Underground); and illustrations for the [[Alex de Campi]] penned ''Twisted Romance: Heartbreak Incorporated'' (2018, [[Image Comics]]), which received a 2019 [[Eisner Awards]] nomination for best anthology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jameskmoran.blogspot.com/2019/05/alex-de-campi-nominated-for-four.html/|title=Alex de Campi Nominated for Four Eisners in 2019|last=Moran|first=James K.|work=(Re)Viewed by James K. Moran|date=May 8, 2019|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmong her early works, Skelly self-published ''Nurse Nurse'' in chapter-sized installments until [[Sparkplug Comics]] founder Dylan Williams offered to publish the collected issues. ''Nurse Nurse'' was one of the last pieces Williams finished publishing before he died in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://robot6.comicbookresources.com/2012/03/sparkplug-turns-to-indiegogo-to-fund-three-final-dylan-williams-projects/|title=Sparkplug turns to IndieGoGo to fund three final Dylan Williams projects|last=Parkin|first=J. K.|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=March 19, 2012|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSkelly has written and lectured about comics for ''[[The Comics Journal]]'', the [[Center for Cartoon Studies]], [[Fordham University]], and [[The New School]], among others. In 2017 she told [[NPR]]: \"When I started drawing comics, it was to make my own reality. But now as an adult, I draw them to better understand why everyday life is extraordinary.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/07/09/535045017/cartoonists-tell-us-what-do-comics-mean-to-you/|title=Cartoonists Tell Us: What Do Comics Mean To You?|last=Mayer|first=Petra|work=[[NPR]]|date=July 9, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCurrently living and working in [[Brooklyn, New York]], Skelly's forthcoming graphic novel ''Maids,'' a biographical graphic novel about convicted murderers [[Christine and L\u00e9a Papin]], will be published by [[Fantagraphics Books]] in October 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacDonald |first=Heidi |date=2019-09-18 |title=SPX 2019 Spotlights Chris Ware, Eddie Campbell, Sponsor Controversy |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/comics/article/81203-spx-2019-spotlights-chris-ware-eddie-campbell-sponsor-controversy.html |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |location= |access-date=2019-09-18|quote=Acclaimed cartoonist [[Jaime Hernandez]] (''Love and Rockets'') appeared in conversation with artist Katie Skelly... Skelly said her next book, ''Maids'', will be about the [[Christine and L\u00e9a Papin|Papin sisters]], French maids who committed a grisly murder in the 1930s. It\u2019s due from Fantagraphics in 2020. }}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nSkelly's first solo exhibition ''Skellyworld'' opened at [[The Naughton Gallery at Queen's|The Naughton Gallery]] at [[Queen's University Belfast]] in [[Northern Ireland]] on August 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naughtongallery.org/Exhibitions/2019/Skellyworld/ |title=SKELLYWORLD |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=August 8, 2019 |website=NaughtonGallery.org |publisher= |access-date=September 18, 2019 |quote=Inspired by gekiga, giallo, bande dessin\u00e9e, science fiction comics, and B movies from the \u201860s and \u201870s, Skelly\u2019s work examines exploitation genres for transgressive elements.  Through her female protagonists, Skelly normalises all manner of female sensuality, encouraging confidence, sense of self, or the power to erase one's self and become an agent, an alias, or a woman on the run.}}</ref> The show offers insights into Skelly's work and artistic process, exhibiting original drawings from all of her major published works, as well as paintings, sketchbooks, video projects, self-produced merchandise, and a 78-card tarot deck that she designed and illustrated. Curatorial notes for the exhibition count [[Gekiga|Japanese comics]], ''[[Bandes dessin\u00e9es|bandes dessin\u00e9e]]'', [[science fiction]] and [[B movie]]s from the 1960s and 1970s as inspiration for Skelly, who \"examines exploitation genres for transgressive elements\" in her work.\n\nHer art has also appeared in group exhibitions, including ''18+'' at Recspec Gallery in [[Austin, Texas|Austin, TX]] (2018); ''Speculative Skins'' at [[The Naughton Gallery at Queen's|The Naughton Gallery]] (2018); ''From Panel to Panel X: C/Overt Movement in Comicana'', at the Medialia Gallery in [[New York City]] (2014), and ''Karma-Con'' at the [[Rubin Museum of Art]] (2012).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.fantagraphics.com/artists/katie-skelly Fantagraphics Books]\n* [http://www.adhousebooks.com/books/operationmargarine.html Adhouse Books]\n* [https://indyworld.com/imprints/sparkplug-books/ Sparkplug Books]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skelly, Katie}}\n[[Category:American women cartoonists]]\n[[Category:American female comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American women illustrators]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n[[Category:People from Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University alumni]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:21st-century American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cartoonist}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolor       = \n| name          =\n| image         = KatieSkelly2019SPX.png\n| imagesize     =\n| alt           =\n| caption       = Skelly speaking at the [[Small Press Expo]] in 2019\n| birth_date    = February 5, 1985\n| birth_place   = [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = American\n| field         = [[comics artist]]\n| training      =\n| movement      =\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n| website       =\n}}\n'''Katie Skelly''' is an American [[comics artist]] and illustrator. She is best known for her [[graphic novels]] ''My Pretty Vampire'', ''Operation Margarine'' and ''Nurse Nurse''.\n\n==Biography==\nKatie Skelly was born in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]. Her father's side of the family operated a newsstand in downtown Bethlehem and he brought her comics from the stand to read. She began drawing her own comics in high school, and after graduating from college, Skelly began her science fiction-themed, ''[[Barbarella (comics)|Barbarella]]''-inspired series ''Nurse, Nurse''. She received a B. A. in Art History from [[Syracuse University]] and followed it with graduate coursework at [[City College of New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcj.com/ugly-is-good-an-interview-with-katie-skelly/|title=\"Ugly Is Good\": An Interview with Katie Skelly|last=Mautner|first=Chris|work=[[The Comics Journal]]|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n\nIn 2017 [[Fantagraphics Books]] published Skelly's first hardcover graphic novel ''My Pretty Vampire'', notable for its \"dramatic colors\" and \"sense of mercurial motion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/it-s-feeding-time-for-my-pretty-vampire-in-this-exclusi-1798265877/|title=It\u2019s feeding time for My Pretty Vampire in this exclusive preview|last=Sava|first=Oliver|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> Inspired by the Italian horror films of [[Dario Argento]] and the early work of comics illustrator [[Jean-Claude Forest]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/my-pretty-vampire-katie-skelly-interview/|title=Katie Skelly Combines Cute Art with Sexy Horror in My Pretty Vampire|last=Lorah|first=Michael C.|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=August 9, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> the story follows a young vampire who escapes captivity by her brother to discover herself through surreal, sensual and often violent adventures in the modern world.\n\nSkelly's other works include ''Operation Margarine'' (2014, [[Adhouse Books]]), for which she was awarded the inaugural Emerging Artist Prize at the [[Cartoon Crossroads Columbus]] Festival in 2015;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartooncrossroadscolumbus.com/guest/2017/Katie%20Skelly|title=Katie Skelly: CXC 2017 Guest Illustrator|last=|first=|work=cartooncrossroadscolumbus.com|date=2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref> ''The Agency'' (2018, [[Fantagraphics Books|Fantagraphics]] Underground); and illustrations for the [[Alex de Campi]] penned ''Twisted Romance: Heartbreak Incorporated'' (2018, [[Image Comics]]), which received a 2019 [[Eisner Awards]] nomination for best anthology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jameskmoran.blogspot.com/2019/05/alex-de-campi-nominated-for-four.html/|title=Alex de Campi Nominated for Four Eisners in 2019|last=Moran|first=James K.|work=(Re)Viewed by James K. Moran|date=May 8, 2019|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAmong her early works, Skelly self-published ''Nurse Nurse'' in chapter-sized installments until [[Sparkplug Comics]] founder Dylan Williams offered to publish the collected issues. ''Nurse Nurse'' was one of the last pieces Williams finished publishing before he died in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://robot6.comicbookresources.com/2012/03/sparkplug-turns-to-indiegogo-to-fund-three-final-dylan-williams-projects/|title=Sparkplug turns to IndieGoGo to fund three final Dylan Williams projects|last=Parkin|first=J. K.|work=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=March 19, 2012|accessdate=September 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSkelly has written and lectured about comics for ''[[The Comics Journal]]'', the [[Center for Cartoon Studies]], [[Fordham University]], and [[The New School]], among others. In 2017 she told [[NPR]]: \"When I started drawing comics, it was to make my own reality. But now as an adult, I draw them to better understand why everyday life is extraordinary.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/07/09/535045017/cartoonists-tell-us-what-do-comics-mean-to-you/|title=Cartoonists Tell Us: What Do Comics Mean To You?|last=Mayer|first=Petra|work=[[NPR]]|date=July 9, 2017|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCurrently living and working in [[Brooklyn, New York]], Skelly's forthcoming graphic novel ''MAIDS,'' a biographical graphic novel about convicted murderers [[Christine and L\u00e9a Papin]], will be published by [[Fantagraphics Books]] in October 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last=MacDonald |first=Heidi |date=2019-09-18 |title=SPX 2019 Spotlights Chris Ware, Eddie Campbell, Sponsor Controversy |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/comics/article/81203-spx-2019-spotlights-chris-ware-eddie-campbell-sponsor-controversy.html |work=[[Publishers Weekly]] |location= |access-date=2019-09-18|quote=Acclaimed cartoonist [[Jaime Hernandez]] (''Love and Rockets'') appeared in conversation with artist Katie Skelly... Skelly said her next book, ''Maids'', will be about the [[Christine and L\u00e9a Papin|Papin sisters]], French maids who committed a grisly murder in the 1930s. It\u2019s due from Fantagraphics in 2020. }}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nSkelly's first solo exhibition ''Skellyworld'' opened at [[The Naughton Gallery at Queen's|The Naughton Gallery]] at [[Queen's University Belfast]] in [[Northern Ireland]] on August 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naughtongallery.org/Exhibitions/2019/Skellyworld/ |title=SKELLYWORLD |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=August 8, 2019 |website=NaughtonGallery.org |publisher= |access-date=September 18, 2019 |quote=Inspired by gekiga, giallo, bande dessin\u00e9e, science fiction comics, and B movies from the \u201860s and \u201870s, Skelly\u2019s work examines exploitation genres for transgressive elements.  Through her female protagonists, Skelly normalises all manner of female sensuality, encouraging confidence, sense of self, or the power to erase one's self and become an agent, an alias, or a woman on the run.}}</ref> The show offers insights into Skelly's work and artistic process, exhibiting original drawings from all of her major published works, as well as paintings, sketchbooks, video projects, self-produced merchandise, and a 78-card tarot deck that she designed and illustrated. Curatorial notes for the exhibition count [[Gekiga|Japanese comics]], ''[[Bandes dessin\u00e9es|bandes dessin\u00e9e]]'', [[science fiction]] and [[B movie]]s from the 1960s and 1970s as inspiration for Skelly, who \"examines exploitation genres for transgressive elements\" in her work.\n\nHer art has also appeared in group exhibitions, including ''18+'' at Recspec Gallery in [[Austin, Texas|Austin, TX]] (2018); ''Speculative Skins'' at [[The Naughton Gallery at Queen's|The Naughton Gallery]] (2018); ''From Panel to Panel X: C/Overt Movement in Comicana'', at the Medialia Gallery in [[New York City]] (2014), and ''Karma-Con'' at the [[Rubin Museum of Art]] (2012).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.fantagraphics.com/artists/katie-skelly Fantagraphics Books]\n* [http://www.adhousebooks.com/books/operationmargarine.html Adhouse Books]\n* [https://indyworld.com/imprints/sparkplug-books/ Sparkplug Books]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skelly, Katie}}\n[[Category:American women cartoonists]]\n[[Category:American female comics artists]]\n[[Category:American comics writers]]\n[[Category:American women illustrators]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n[[Category:People from Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University alumni]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Artists from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:21st-century American artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Aalazaro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katie_Skelly"}
{"title_page": "Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology", "text_new": "{{Infobox Museum\n |name          = Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology\n |image         = Royal Tyrrell Museum from the staircase.jpg\n |imagesize     = \n |caption       = Entrance to the Royal Tyrrell Museum\n |map_type      = \n |map_caption   = \n |coordinates   = {{coord|51.479361|-112.789278|display=inline, title}}\n |established   = {{start date and age|1985|09|25|df=y}}\n |dissolved     =\n |location      = 1500 N Dinosaur Trail,<br>[[Drumheller]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n |type          = [[paleontology|Palaeontological]]\n |visitors      = 470,000 (2016\u201317)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.assembly.ab.ca/LADDAR_files/docs/committees/pa/legislature_29/session_4/20180313_0830_01_pa.pdf#page=6|title=Standing Committee on Public Accounts|publisher=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|website=docs.assembly.ab.ca|accessdate=7 April 2020|date=13 March 2018|page=646}}</ref>\n |executive_director      = ''Vacant''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/about/directors_staff|title=Directors & Staff|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref>\n |publictransit =\n |architect = BCW Architects\n |website       = {{url|https://tyrrellmuseum.com}}\n}}\nThe '''Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology''' ('''RTMP''') is a palaeontology museum and research facility in [[Drumheller]], [[Alberta]], Canada. The museum is situated within a {{convert|12500|m2|sqft|adj=mid|-building}} designed by BCW Architects at [[Midland Provincial Park]]. \n\nThe museum was established in September 1985, with many of its initial staff, and items from the collection originating from the [[Provincial Museum of Alberta]]. Initially named the '''Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology''', the museum was later renamed the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology in June 1990, following its bestowal of the title \"royal\" from Queen [[Elizabeth II]]. The museum saw the expansion of its building twice in the 21st century. The first expansion was designed by BCW Architects, and was completed in 2003; while the second expansion was designed by Kasian Architecture, and was completed in 2019.\n\nThe museum's personal collection includes over 160,000 cataloged fossils, consisting of over 350 [[holotype]]s. The museum displays approximately 800 fossils from its collection in its museum exhibits. In addition to exhibits, the museum's fossil collection are also used by the museum's research program, which carries a mandate to document and analyze geological and palaeontological history.\n\n== History ==\nDuring the late 1970s, the government of Alberta began to consider building a within, or adjacent to [[Dinosaur Provincial Park]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} In 1981, the provincial government formally announced plans to build a palaeontology museum.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} However, the museum was built in [[Midland Provincial Park]] near [[Drumheller]], as opposed to Dinosaur Provincial Park.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} The construction of the museum formed a part of a larger initiative from [[Premier of Alberta|premier]] [[Peter Lougheed]], to establish a network of provincially-operated museums and interprative centres in select small towns and rural areas throughout Alberta.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} The provincial government had allocated [[Canadian dollar|C$]]30 million to build the museum.<ref name=drumheller1>{{cite web|url=https://www.drumhellermail.com/8969-qlet-my-imagination-run-riotq-baird-recalls-museums-origin|title=\"Let my imagination run riot,\" Baird recalls museum's origin|date=17 September 2010|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=www.drumhellermail.com|publisher=The Drumheller Mail}}</ref> The development of the museum was largely led by the institution's first director, David Baird.<ref name=drumheller1/>\n\nA large portion of the museum's original staff, and fossil collection was spun off from the [[Royal Alberta Museum|Provincial Museum of Alberta]]'s palaeontology program.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} The staff of the future palaeontology museum worked in a temporary office space in [[downtown Edmonton]] until 1982, when they were relocated to another temporary office, laborary, and workshop in Drumheller.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} Prior to opening, the museum's informal working name was the ''Palaeontological Museum and Research Institute'', although it was changed by Baird to the Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology, in honour of [[Joseph Tyrrell]], a geologist of the [[Geological Survey of Canada]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} During his time in Red Deer River valley, Tyrrell accidentally discovered the first reported dinosaur fossil that area in 1884 while searching for coal seams.<ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite book|last1=Barnes|first1=Michael|title=Fortunes in the Ground|date=1986|publisher=The Boston Mills Press|location=Erin, Ontario|isbn=091978352X|page=198,221}}</ref> \n[[File:Sinraptor dongi.jpg|thumb|left|Skeletal model of a ''[[Sinraptor]]'', a species identified during the Sino-Canadian Dinosaur Project during the mid-1980s to 1990s, co-led by RTMP]]\nThe Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology was opened to the public on 25 September 1985.<ref name=canen>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/royal-tyrrell-museum-of-palaeontology|title=Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=26 March 2020|date=8 April 2015|publisher=Historica Canada|last=Reid|first=Monty}}</ref> In the same year, the museum announced its first collaborative, out-of-province research project, the Sino-Canadian Dinosaur Project. The collaborative effort marked the first meaningful collaboration between Chinese and [[western world|western]] palaeontologists since the [[Chinese Communist Revolution]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=9}}\n\nOn 28 June 1990, the museum was bestowed the title ''royal'' by Queen [[Elizabeth II]].<ref name=canen/> The museum's volunteer [[support group]], the Royal Tyrrell Museum Cooperating Society, was formed in 1993, and helps fund museum-sanctioned research projects, publications, postdoctoral fellowships, and other museum-centred events.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}}\n\nIn 2003, the museum completed its first major expansion to its building, completing the ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre annex.<ref name=albertview>{{cite web|url=https://albertaviews.ab.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/AV-media-guide-2014-PQ.pdf|title=2014 Media Guide|website=albertaviews.ab.ca|publisher=Alberta Views|year=2013|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nPlans to expand the museum's building again were underway as early as 2013, although the museum did not announce its plans to expand the museum building until 2016.<ref name=drumhell2>{{cite web|url=https://www.drumhellermail.com/news/30033-contractor-picked-for-tyrrell-expansion|title=Contractor picked for Tyrrell expansion|last=Kolafa|first=Pat|website=www.drumhellermail.com|publisher=The Drumheller Mail|date=16 August 2017|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The expansion plan saw the construction of a learning lounge annex, that increased the building's size by an additional {{convert|1300|m2|sqft}}.<ref name=drumhel>{{cite web|url=https://www.drumhellermail.com/news/29289-tyrrell-9-million-expansion-breaks-ground-in-new-year|title=Tyrrell $9 million expansion breaks ground in new year|last=Kolafa|first=Pat|website=www.drumhellermail.com|publisher=The Drumheller Mail|date=23 December 2016|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The learning lounge annex was created in response to the feedback received from the museum, which requested more hands-on exhibits and activities at the museum.<ref name=calher>{{cite web|url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/interactive-albertosaurus-exhibit-opens-at-expanded-royal-tyrrell-museum/|title=Interactive Albertosaurus exhibit opens at expanded Royal Tyrrell Museum|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|work=Calgary Herald|last=Cole|first=Yolande|date=28 June 2019}}</ref> The expansion for the museum was funded by the governments of Alberta, and Canada and cost cost approximately C$9.3 million.<ref name=cbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/royal-tyrrell-museum-expansion-federal-funding-1.3936436|title=Royal Tyrrell Museum expansion gets $3.5M in federal funding|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|work=CBC News|date=14 January 2017|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The provincial government provided C$5.7 million, the majority of the funds for the expansion, while the remaining C$3.5 million was provided by the federal government.<ref name=cbc/> The expansion marks the first time the museum's received cultural infrastructure funding from the federal government of Canada.<ref name=cbc/> The expansion was formally opened to the public in June 2019.<ref name=calher/>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Royal Tyrrell Museum from the viewpoint.jpg|thumb|The design of the museum building attempts to harmonize itself with the surrounding [[badlands]]]]\nThe museum is located on North Dinosaur Trail at Midland Provincial Park, in [[Drumheller]], Alberta, and is situated in a building purposely designed to be a museum, and as a laboratory/research facility.<ref name=canen/> The original structure was completed in 1985, and was expanded twice in the 21st century. The original structure and its first expansion has a total area of {{convert|121000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of space.<ref name=albertview/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyrrellmuseum.com/info/index2.php?strSection=5|title = Museum Amenities|accessdate=18 July 2008|website=tyrrellmuseum.com|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum Cooperating Society|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516132856/http://www.tyrrellmuseum.com/info/index2.php?strSection=5|archivedate=16 May 2008}}</ref> The original structure, with its first expansion holds approximately {{convert|4400|m2|sqft}} worth of exhibit space.<ref name=canen/><ref name=albertview/> The building's second expansion annex comprise approximately {{convert|1300|m2|sqft}} of space, bringing the approximate total area of the museum building to {{convert|12500|m2|sqft}}.\n\nThe original building was designed by the [[Calgary]]-based BCW Architects, with Doug Craig as the lead architect.<ref name=drumheller1/><ref name=albertview/> Although the design was largely left to Craig, he was given a list of 27 architectural requirements for the building from Baird.<ref name=drumheller1/> Several of these requirements included the necessity to harmonize the building with the surrounding [[badlands]], make the entrance easy to locate by routing the driveway to pass the front of the building, and providing adequate space for visitors' eyes to adjust from the light outside and inside the building.<ref name=drumheller1/> The main structure includes several galleries with interactive displays, a cafeteria, gift shop, and a theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bcw-arch.com/projects/civic-cultural-care-faculties/royal-tyrell-museum/|title=Royal Tyrell Museum of Palaeontology|publisher=BCW Architects|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=bcw-arch.com}}</ref> The museum's main lobby features a mural made of ten {{convert|4|by|8|ft|m|order=flip|adj=mid}} ceramic panels, titled ''The Story of Life'' and crafted by [[Lorraine Malach]].\n\nThe museum contracted BCW Architects was contracted again to help design the ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre, a {{convert|1485|m2|sqft|adj=mid|-annex}} to the main museum.<ref name=albertview/><ref name=bcw>{{cite web|url=https://bcw-arch.com/projects/civic-cultural-care-faculties/atco-tyrell-learning-centre%E2%80%A8/|title=Royal Tyrell Museum Learning Centre|publisher=BCW Architects|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=bcw-arch.com}}</ref> The ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre was completed in 2003 and included several classrooms with distance learning technology to allows researchers to remotely connect with field sites, and a laboratory.<ref name=albertview/><ref name=bcw/> The ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre was designed to accommodate students from [[elementary education|elementary]] to [[post-secondary education|post-secondary]] levels of education.<ref name=bcw/> \n[[File:Drumheller Pachyrhinosaurus.jpg|thumb|left|A sculpture of a ''[[Pachyrhinosaurus]]'' in front of the ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre, an annex of the building completed in 2003]]\nIn 2019, the museum completed construction of a learning lounge annex approximately {{convert|1300|m2|sqft}}.<ref name=drumhel/> The expansion for the museum was designed by Kasian Architecture, along with the museum, and the government of Alberta.<ref name=drumhel/> LEAR Construction, a Calgary-based construction firm, was awarded the contract to construct the expansion.<ref name=drumhell2/> The expansion saw the Distance Learning Studio, and accessible washrooms enlarged, as well as the creation of additional classrooms, laboratory spaces, an interactive learning lounge and rest area, and other multipurpose rooms.<ref name=drumhel/>\n\n==Exhibits==\nAs of 2020, the museum building houses thirteen exhibits that display approximately 800 fossils on permanent display.<ref name=canen/><ref name=exhib>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits|title=Exhibits|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Audio-visual, interactive computers, and video programs and displays typically provide relevant information on the items in the exhibit.<ref name=canen/> A number of these exhibits are organized by [[Era (geology)|geologic eras]], displaying specimens from those periods. These exhibits includes [[Cenozoic]] Gallery, [[Cretaceous]] Alberta, Cretaceous Garden, [[Palaeozoic]] Era, and Terrestrial Palaeozoic. Other exhibits that display specimens from the museum's fossil collection includes the Dinosaur Hall, Fossils in Focus, and Triassic Giants.<ref name=exhib/> Dinosaur Hall houses over thirty mounted dinosaur skeletons including specimens of a ''[[Albertosaurus]]'', ''[[Camarasaurus]]'', ''[[Triceratops]]'', and a ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]''.<ref name=canen/> Fossils in Focus was an exhibit that typically displaying specimens that are of focus for the museum's research program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/fossils_in_focus|title=Fossils in Focus|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Triassic Giants was an exhibit dedicated to Elizabeth Nicholls, the museum's former curator of marine reptiles, and houses a specimen of a ''[[shonisaurus]]'', the world's largest marine reptile.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/triassic_giant|title=Triassic Giants|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> \n[[File:Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.jpg|thumb|Panorama of Dinosaur Hall, an exhibit that houses a number of dinosaur skeletal frames]]\nAlong with exhibits that are primarily concerned with the exhibition of specimens, the museum also has two exhibits related on palaeontology, ''Foundations'', and ''Preperation Lab''; the latter exhibit allowing visitors to watch technicians as they prepare fossils for exhibits or research.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/foundations|title=Foundations|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/preparation_lab|title=Preperation Lab|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Several exhibits are also organized by locale, or focused on a specific [[Lagerst\u00e4tte|fossil-bearing deposit]], such as the Burgess Shale exhibit. The Grounds for Discovery exhibit displays specimens found from commercial and industrial digs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/burgess_shale|title=Burgess Shale|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/grounds_for_discovery|title=Grounds for Discovery|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> \n\nOther exhibits in the museum includes the Cretaceous Garden, which was designed to mimic the Albertan environment during the Cretaceous era by planting living relatives of the vegetation that grew in Alberta during that era.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/cretaceous_garden|title=Cretaceous Garden|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Opened in 2019, the Learning Lounge is the museum's newest exhibit, and serves as the museum's interactive and hands-on exhibit, and includes a bronze statue of an ''[[Albertosaurus]]'', and interactive displays on how dinosaurs ate, moved, and interacted with other organisms.<ref name=calher/> \n\n==Collections==\n[[File:Nodosaur.jpg|thumb|A ''[[Borealopelta]]'' on display. The specimen is one of many from the collection that was found in Alberta]]\nAs of 2020, the museum's collection held approximately 160,000 cataloged fossils, consisting of over 350 [[holotype]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/natureofthings/m_features/100-million-years-ago-alberta-was-a-giant-sea-surrounded-by-tropical-forest|title=100 million years ago, Alberta was a giant sea surrounded by tropical forests|work=CBC Docs|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|last=Duggan|first=Graham}}</ref><ref name=collection>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/research/collections|title=Collections|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Items from the collection are either used for research, or for museum exhibits. Approximately 0.5 per cent of the museum's collection are placed on display.<ref name=collection/> \n\nApproximately half of these items are fossils dating back to the Cretaceous period.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=13}} The majority of these fossils originate from Alberta, with approximately 85 per cent of the fossils from the province being collected from the museum's fieldwork.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=13}} In addition to the Cretaceous fossils of Alberta, the museum also holds a number of fossils from the [[Palaeocene]] of Alberta, the Palaeozoic of the [[Canadian Arctic]], and in the Palaeozoic, [[Triassic]], and early Cretaceous of British Columbia.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} \n\nThe museum has a number of items in its collection that were not acquired through fieldwork. through purchases, exchanges, donations, salvage operations of industrial excavations, and from palaeontologists archiving their works at the museum.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} Most of the specimens that were purchased were acquired in the early 1980s, when the museum had a large acquisition budget.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} Approximately 3,000 specimens are added to the collection annually.<ref name=collection/>\n\n==Programs==\n[[File:California Academy of Sciences - Interior 6 2017-06-09.jpg|thumb|A replica of a ''Tyrannosaurus'' from the RTMP's collection at the [[California Academy of Sciences]]. The RTMP produces replicas of specimens from its collection for other museums to use.]]\nGuided tours of the surrounding Midland Provincial Park are offered by the museum staff.<ref name=canen/> The museum also operate several outreach programs, providing students hands-on field training, and conducting several \"pay-to-dig\" programs in the Drumheller area, where members of the public participated in [[bonebed]] excavation.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=18}} \n\nThe museum operates a program casting and molding program, creating replicas of specimens in the museum's collections, for use in other museum.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} \n\n===Research===\n[[File:Royal Tyrell fossil lab.jpg|thumb|A member of the museum staff working on a fossil in the museum's preperation laboratory]]\nThe museum research program has a broad mandate to document and analyze geological and palaeontological history, with reference to Alberta.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} The museum's research program includes a palaeontological research group, as well as a rotating roster of postdoctoral fellows and graduate students.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} Palaeontological technicians of the museum assist, or oversee fieldwork operations; as well as prepare fossils for exhibits, or research.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} In 2015, the museum's group of research technicians had collectively over 150 years of cumulative experience.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} Although formally not employed for the purposes of research, palaeontological technicians have performed independent, or collaborative research projects at the museum in the past.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} \n\nThe majority of the research papers authored by members of the museum's research program is devoted to [[vertebrates]], with less than 40 papers published in 2015 that deal with either macro plants, [[palynomorph]]s, and [[invertebrates]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=19}} Findings from the research program are regularly incorporated into the museum's exhibits, and educational outreach progarms.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=15}} \n\nThe museum's research team was initially founded in the early 1980s, and was initially tasked with searching for specimens for the museum's exhibits and collections.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=11}} After the demand for exhibit-quality specimens was met, the museum's researchers were reoriented towards documenting and interpreting the geology, and fossils of Midland Provincial Park, Dinosaur Provincial Park, and other areas in the province.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=12}}<ref name=naylor1997>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Dinosaurs | title = Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology | last = Naylor | first = Bruce G. | editor = Currie, Philip J. |editor2=Padian, Kevin | year = 1997 | publisher = [[Academic Press]] | isbn = 0-12-226810-5 | pages = 646}}</ref> The museum has maintained a {{convert|500|m2|sqft|adj=mid}} permanent field station at Dinosaur Provincial Park since 1987.<ref name=canen/> Other areas in Canada where the museum's research program has conducted fieldwork includes British Columbia, the Canadian Arctic, [[Manitoba]], and [[Saskatchewan]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=13}} \n\nThe museum has conducted a number of research collaborations with other institutions, including the Geological Survey of Canada, [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]], other museums in North America, and universities based in Alberta.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} Many of the museum's research projects are based in Alberta, although it has conducted research projects out of the province. As of 2015, the museum has participated in 10 collaborative, and externally-funded research projects outside of Alberta, the first being the Sino-Canadian Dinosaur Project in 1985.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=9}} As of 2015, these collaborative, out-of-province research projects has resulted in over 75 research publications.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=9}} \n\n==See also==\n* [[List of museums in Alberta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=James D.|last2=Henderson|first2=Donald M.|last3=Therrien|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Introduction to the Special Issue commemorating the 30th anniversary of the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology, with a summary of the museum\u2019s early history and its research contributions|journal=Canadian Journal of Earth Science|year=2015|volume=52|issue=8|page=5\u201333|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Royal Tyrrell Museum}}\n* {{official|https://tyrrellmuseum.com}}\n\n{{portal bar|Canada|Museums|Palaeontology}}\n{{Alberta parks}}\n\n[[Category:Museums in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Natural history museums in Canada]]\n[[Category:Burgess Shale fossils]]\n[[Category:Provincial historic sites of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Canada with royal patronage]]\n[[Category:Fossil museums]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Drumheller]]\n[[Category:Dinosaur museums]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Canada]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Alberta]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Museum\n |name          = Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology\n |image         = Royal Tyrrell Museum from the staircase.jpg\n |imagesize     = \n |caption       = Entrance to the Royal Tyrrell Museum\n |map_type      = \n |map_caption   = \n |coordinates   = {{coord|51.479361|-112.789278|display=inline, title}}\n |established   = {{start date and age|1985|09|25|df=y}}\n |dissolved     =\n |location      = 1500 N Dinosaur Trail,<br>[[Drumheller]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n |type          = [[paleontology|Palaeontological]]\n |visitors      = 470,000 (2016\u201317)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.assembly.ab.ca/LADDAR_files/docs/committees/pa/legislature_29/session_4/20180313_0830_01_pa.pdf#page=6|title=Standing Committee on Public Accounts|publisher=Legislative Assembly of Alberta|website=docs.assembly.ab.ca|accessdate=7 April 2020|date=13 March 2018|page=646}}</ref>\n |executive_director      = ''Vacant''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/about/directors_staff|title=Directors & Staff|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref>\n |publictransit =\n |architect = BCW Architects\n |website       = {{url|https://tyrrellmuseum.com}}\n}}\nThe '''Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology''' ('''RTMP''') is a palaeontology museum and research facility in [[Drumheller]], [[Alberta]], Canada. The museum is situated within a {{convert|12500|m2|sqft|adj=mid|-building}} designed by BCW Architects at [[Midland Provincial Park]]. \n\nThe museum was established in September 1985, with many of its initial staff, and items from the collection originating from the [[Provincial Museum of Alberta]]. Initially named the '''Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology''', the museum was later renamed the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology in June 1990, following its bestowal of the title \"royal\" from Queen [[Elizabeth II]]. The museum saw the expansion of its building twice in the 21st century. The first expansion was designed by BCW Architects, and was completed in 2003; while the second expansion was designed by Kasian Architecture, and was completed in 2019.\n\nThe museum's personal collection includes over 160,000 cataloged fossils, consisting of over 350 [[holotype]]s. The museum displays approximately 800 fossils from its collection in its museum exhibits. In addition to exhibits, the museum's fossil collection are also used by the museum's research program, which carries a mandate to document and analyze geological and palaeontological history.\n\n== History ==\nDuring the late 1970s, the government of Alberta began to consider building a within, or adjacent to [[Dinosaur Provincial Park]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} In 1981, the provincial government formally announced plans to build a palaeontology museum.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} However, the museum was built in [[Midland Provincial Park]] near [[Drumheller]], as opposed to Dinosaur Provincial Park.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} The construction of the museum formed a part of a larger initiative from [[Premier of Alberta|premier]] [[Peter Lougheed]], to establish a network of provincially-operated museums and interprative centres in select small towns and rural areas throughout Alberta.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} The provincial government had allocated [[Canadian dollar|C$]]30 million to build the museum.<ref name=drumheller1>{{cite web|url=https://www.drumhellermail.com/8969-qlet-my-imagination-run-riotq-baird-recalls-museums-origin|title=\"Let my imagination run riot,\" Baird recalls museum's origin|date=17 September 2010|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=www.drumhellermail.com|publisher=The Drumheller Mail}}</ref> The development of the museum was largely led by the institution's first director, David Baird.<ref name=drumheller1/>\n\nA large portion of the museum's original staff, and fossil collection was spun off from the [[Royal Alberta Museum|Provincial Museum of Alberta]]'s palaeontology program.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} The staff of the future palaeontology museum worked in a temporary office space in [[downtown Edmonton]] until 1982, when they were relocated to another temporary office, laborary, and workshop in Drumheller.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} Prior to opening, the museum's informal working name was the ''Palaeontological Museum and Research Institute'', although it was changed by Baird to the Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology, in honour of [[Joseph Tyrrell]], a geologist of the [[Geological Survey of Canada]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=7}} During his time in Red Deer River valley, Tyrrell accidentally discovered the first reported dinosaur fossil that area in 1884 while searching for coal seams.<ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite book|last1=Barnes|first1=Michael|title=Fortunes in the Ground|date=1986|publisher=The Boston Mills Press|location=Erin, Ontario|isbn=091978352X|page=198,221}}</ref> \n[[File:Sinraptor dongi.jpg|thumb|left|Skeletal model of a ''[[Sinraptor]]'', a species identified during the Sino-Canadian Dinosaur Project during the mid-1980s to 1990s, co-led by RTMP]]\nThe Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology was opened to the public on 25 September 1985.<ref name=canen>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/royal-tyrrell-museum-of-palaeontology|title=Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=26 March 2020|date=8 April 2015|publisher=Historica Canada|last=Reid|first=Monty}}</ref> In the same year, the museum announced its first collaborative, out-of-province research project, the Sino-Canadian Dinosaur Project. The collaborative effort marked the first meaningful collaboration between Chinese and [[western world|western]] palaeontologists since the [[Chinese Communist Revolution]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=9}}\n\nOn 28 June 1990, the museum was bestowed the title ''royal'' by Queen [[Elizabeth II]].<ref name=canen/> The museum's volunteer [[support group]], the Royal Tyrrell Museum Cooperating Society, was formed in 1993, and helps fund museum-sanctioned research projects, publications, postdoctoral fellowships, and other museum-centred events.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}}\n\nIn 2003, the museum completed its first major expansion to its building, completing the ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre annex.<ref name=albertview>{{cite web|url=https://albertaviews.ab.ca/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/AV-media-guide-2014-PQ.pdf|title=2014 Media Guide|website=albertaviews.ab.ca|publisher=Alberta Views|year=2013|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nPlans to expand the museum's building again were underway as early as 2013, although the museum did not announce its plans to expand the museum building until 2016.<ref name=drumhell2>{{cite web|url=https://www.drumhellermail.com/news/30033-contractor-picked-for-tyrrell-expansion|title=Contractor picked for Tyrrell expansion|last=Kolafa|first=Pat|website=www.drumhellermail.com|publisher=The Drumheller Mail|date=16 August 2017|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The expansion plan saw the construction of a learning lounge annex, that increased the building's size by an additional {{convert|1300|m2|sqft}}.<ref name=drumhel>{{cite web|url=https://www.drumhellermail.com/news/29289-tyrrell-9-million-expansion-breaks-ground-in-new-year|title=Tyrrell $9 million expansion breaks ground in new year|last=Kolafa|first=Pat|website=www.drumhellermail.com|publisher=The Drumheller Mail|date=23 December 2016|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The learning lounge annex was created in response to the feedback received from the museum, which requested more hands-on exhibits and activities at the museum.<ref name=calher>{{cite web|url=https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/interactive-albertosaurus-exhibit-opens-at-expanded-royal-tyrrell-museum/|title=Interactive Albertosaurus exhibit opens at expanded Royal Tyrrell Museum|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|work=Calgary Herald|last=Cole|first=Yolande|date=28 June 2019}}</ref> The expansion for the museum was funded by the governments of Alberta, and Canada and cost cost approximately C$9.3 million.<ref name=cbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/royal-tyrrell-museum-expansion-federal-funding-1.3936436|title=Royal Tyrrell Museum expansion gets $3.5M in federal funding|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|work=CBC News|date=14 January 2017|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref> The provincial government provided C$5.7 million, the majority of the funds for the expansion, while the remaining C$3.5 million was provided by the federal government.<ref name=cbc/> The expansion marks the first time the museum's received cultural infrastructure funding from the federal government of Canada.<ref name=cbc/> The expansion was formally opened to the public in June 2019.<ref name=calher/>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Royal Tyrrell Museum from the viewpoint.jpg|thumb|The design of the museum building attempts to harmonize itself with the surrounding [[badlands]]]]\nThe museum is located on North Dinosaur Trail at Midland Provincial Park, in [[Drumheller]], Alberta, and is situated in a building purposely designed to be a museum, and as a laboratory/research facility.<ref name=canen/> The original structure was completed in 1985, and was expanded twice in the 21st century. The original structure and its first expansion has a total area of {{convert|121000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} of space.<ref name=albertview/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tyrrellmuseum.com/info/index2.php?strSection=5|title = Museum Amenities|accessdate=18 July 2008|website=tyrrellmuseum.com|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum Cooperating Society|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516132856/http://www.tyrrellmuseum.com/info/index2.php?strSection=5|archivedate=16 May 2008}}</ref> The original structure, with its first expansion holds approximately {{convert|4400|m2|sqft}} worth of exhibit space.<ref name=canen/><ref name=albertview/> The building's second expansion annex comprise approximately {{convert|1300|m2|sqft}} of space, bringing the approximate total area of the museum building to {{convert|12500|m2|sqft}}.\n\nThe original building was designed by the [[Calgary]]-based BCW Architects, with Doug Craig as the lead architect.<ref name=albertview/><ref name=drumheller1/> Although the design was largely left to Craig, he was given a list of 27 architectural requirements for the building from Baird.<ref name=drumheller1/> Several of these requirements included the necessity to harmonize the building with the surrounding [[badlands]], make the entrance easy to locate by routing the driveway to pass the front of the building, and providing adequate space for visitors' eyes to adjust from the light outside and inside the building.<ref name=drumheller1/> The main structure includes several galleries with interactive displays, a cafeteria, gift shop, and a theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bcw-arch.com/projects/civic-cultural-care-faculties/royal-tyrell-museum/|title=Royal Tyrell Museum of Palaeontology|publisher=BCW Architects|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=bcw-arch.com}}</ref> The museum's main lobby features a mural made of ten {{convert|4|by|8|ft|m|order=flip|adj=mid}} ceramic panels, titled ''The Story of Life'' and crafted by [[Lorraine Malach]].\n\nThe museum contracted BCW Architects was contracted again to help design the ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre, a {{convert|1485|m2|sqft|adj=mid|-annex}} to the main museum.<ref name=albertview/><ref name=bcw>{{cite web|url=https://bcw-arch.com/projects/civic-cultural-care-faculties/atco-tyrell-learning-centre%E2%80%A8/|title=Royal Tyrell Museum Learning Centre|publisher=BCW Architects|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=bcw-arch.com}}</ref> The ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre was completed in 2003 and included several classrooms with distance learning technology to allows researchers to remotely connect with field sites, and a laboratory.<ref name=albertview/><ref name=bcw/> The ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre was designed to accommodate students from [[elementary education|elementary]] to [[post-secondary education|post-secondary]] levels of education.<ref name=bcw/> \n[[File:Drumheller Pachyrhinosaurus.jpg|thumb|left|A sculpture of a ''[[Pachyrhinosaurus]]'' in front of the ATCO Tyrrell Learning Centre, an annex of the building completed in 2003]]\nIn 2019, the museum completed construction of a learning lounge annex approximately {{convert|1300|m2|sqft}}.<ref name=drumhel/> The expansion for the museum was designed by Kasian Architecture, along with the museum, and the government of Alberta.<ref name=drumhel/> LEAR Construction, a Calgary-based construction firm, was awarded the contract to construct the expansion.<ref name=drumhell2/> The expansion saw the Distance Learning Studio, and accessible washrooms enlarged, as well as the creation of additional classrooms, laboratory spaces, an interactive learning lounge and rest area, and other multipurpose rooms.<ref name=drumhel/>\n\n==Exhibits==\nAs of 2020, the museum building houses thirteen exhibits that display approximately 800 fossils on permanent display.<ref name=canen/><ref name=exhib>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits|title=Exhibits|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Audio-visual, interactive computers, and video programs and displays typically provide relevant information on the items in the exhibit.<ref name=canen/> A number of these exhibits are organized by [[Era (geology)|geologic eras]], displaying specimens from those periods. These exhibits includes [[Cenozoic]] Gallery, [[Cretaceous]] Alberta, Cretaceous Garden, [[Palaeozoic]] Era, and Terrestrial Palaeozoic. Other exhibits that display specimens from the museum's fossil collection includes the Dinosaur Hall, Fossils in Focus, and Triassic Giants.<ref name=exhib/> Dinosaur Hall houses over thirty mounted dinosaur skeletons including specimens of a ''[[Albertosaurus]]'', ''[[Camarasaurus]]'', ''[[Triceratops]]'', and a ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]''.<ref name=canen/> Fossils in Focus was an exhibit that typically displaying specimens that are of focus for the museum's research program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/fossils_in_focus|title=Fossils in Focus|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Triassic Giants was an exhibit dedicated to Elizabeth Nicholls, the museum's former curator of marine reptiles, and houses a specimen of a ''[[shonisaurus]]'', the world's largest marine reptile.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/triassic_giant|title=Triassic Giants|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> \n[[File:Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.jpg|thumb|Panorama of Dinosaur Hall, an exhibit that houses a number of dinosaur skeletal frames]]\nAlong with exhibits that are primarily concerned with the exhibition of specimens, the museum also has two exhibits related on palaeontology, ''Foundations'', and ''Preperation Lab''; the latter exhibit allowing visitors to watch technicians as they prepare fossils for exhibits or research.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/foundations|title=Foundations|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/preparation_lab|title=Preperation Lab|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Several exhibits are also organized by locale, or focused on a specific [[Lagerst\u00e4tte|fossil-bearing deposit]], such as the Burgess Shale exhibit. The Grounds for Discovery exhibit displays specimens found from commercial and industrial digs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/burgess_shale|title=Burgess Shale|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/grounds_for_discovery|title=Grounds for Discovery|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> \n\nOther exhibits in the museum includes the Cretaceous Garden, which was designed to mimic the Albertan environment during the Cretaceous era by planting living relatives of the vegetation that grew in Alberta during that era.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/whats_on/exhibits/cretaceous_garden|title=Cretaceous Garden|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Opened in 2019, the Learning Lounge is the museum's newest exhibit, and serves as the museum's interactive and hands-on exhibit, and includes a bronze statue of an ''[[Albertosaurus]]'', and interactive displays on how dinosaurs ate, moved, and interacted with other organisms.<ref name=calher/> \n\n==Collections==\n[[File:Nodosaur.jpg|thumb|A ''[[Borealopelta]]'' on display. The specimen is one of many from the collection that was found in Alberta]]\nAs of 2020, the museum's collection held approximately 160,000 cataloged fossils, consisting of over 350 [[holotype]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/natureofthings/m_features/100-million-years-ago-alberta-was-a-giant-sea-surrounded-by-tropical-forest|title=100 million years ago, Alberta was a giant sea surrounded by tropical forests|work=CBC Docs|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=9 January 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|last=Duggan|first=Graham}}</ref><ref name=collection>{{cite web|url=https://tyrrellmuseum.com/research/collections|title=Collections|publisher=Royal Tyrrell Museum|year=2020|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=tyrrellmuseum.com}}</ref> Items from the collection are either used for research, or for museum exhibits. Approximately 0.5 per cent of the museum's collection are placed on display.<ref name=collection/> \n\nApproximately half of these items are fossils dating back to the Cretaceous period.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=13}} The majority of these fossils originate from Alberta, with approximately 85 per cent of the fossils from the province being collected from the museum's fieldwork.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=13}} In addition to the Cretaceous fossils of Alberta, the museum also holds a number of fossils from the [[Palaeocene]] of Alberta, the Palaeozoic of the [[Canadian Arctic]], and in the Palaeozoic, [[Triassic]], and early Cretaceous of British Columbia.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} \n\nThe museum has a number of items in its collection that were not acquired through fieldwork. through purchases, exchanges, donations, salvage operations of industrial excavations, and from palaeontologists archiving their works at the museum.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} Most of the specimens that were purchased were acquired in the early 1980s, when the museum had a large acquisition budget.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} Approximately 3,000 specimens are added to the collection annually.<ref name=collection/>\n\n==Programs==\n[[File:California Academy of Sciences - Interior 6 2017-06-09.jpg|thumb|A replica of a ''Tyrannosaurus'' from the RTMP's collection at the [[California Academy of Sciences]]. The RTMP produces replicas of specimens from its collection for other museums to use.]]\nGuided tours of the surrounding Midland Provincial Park are offered by the museum staff.<ref name=canen/> The museum also operate several outreach programs, providing students hands-on field training, and conducting several \"pay-to-dig\" programs in the Drumheller area, where members of the public participated in [[bonebed]] excavation.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=18}} \n\nThe museum operates a program casting and molding program, creating replicas of specimens in the museum's collections, for use in other museum.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} \n\n===Research===\n[[File:Royal Tyrell fossil lab.jpg|thumb|A member of the museum staff working on a fossil in the museum's preperation laboratory]]\nThe museum research program has a broad mandate to document and analyze geological and palaeontological history, with reference to Alberta.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=14}} The museum's research program includes a palaeontological research group, as well as a rotating roster of postdoctoral fellows and graduate students.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} Palaeontological technicians of the museum assist, or oversee fieldwork operations; as well as prepare fossils for exhibits, or research.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} In 2015, the museum's group of research technicians had collectively over 150 years of cumulative experience.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} Although formally not employed for the purposes of research, palaeontological technicians have performed independent, or collaborative research projects at the museum in the past.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} \n\nThe majority of the research papers authored by members of the museum's research program is devoted to [[vertebrates]], with less than 40 papers published in 2015 that deal with either macro plants, [[palynomorph]]s, and [[invertebrates]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=19}} Findings from the research program are regularly incorporated into the museum's exhibits, and educational outreach progarms.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=15}} \n\nThe museum's research team was initially founded in the early 1980s, and was initially tasked with searching for specimens for the museum's exhibits and collections.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=11}} After the demand for exhibit-quality specimens was met, the museum's researchers were reoriented towards documenting and interpreting the geology, and fossils of Midland Provincial Park, Dinosaur Provincial Park, and other areas in the province.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=12}}<ref name=naylor1997>{{cite encyclopedia | encyclopedia = Encyclopedia of Dinosaurs | title = Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology | last = Naylor | first = Bruce G. | editor = Currie, Philip J. |editor2=Padian, Kevin | year = 1997 | publisher = [[Academic Press]] | isbn = 0-12-226810-5 | pages = 646}}</ref> The museum has maintained a {{convert|500|m2|sqft|adj=mid}} permanent field station at Dinosaur Provincial Park since 1987.<ref name=canen/> Other areas in Canada where the museum's research program has conducted fieldwork includes British Columbia, the Canadian Arctic, [[Manitoba]], and [[Saskatchewan]].{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=13}} \n\nThe museum has conducted a number of research collaborations with other institutions, including the Geological Survey of Canada, [[Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology]], other museums in North America, and universities based in Alberta.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=8}} Many of the museum's research projects are based in Alberta, although it has conducted research projects out of the province. As of 2015, the museum has participated in 10 collaborative, and externally-funded research projects outside of Alberta, the first being the Sino-Canadian Dinosaur Project in 1985.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=9}} As of 2015, these collaborative, out-of-province research projects has resulted in over 75 research publications.{{sfn|Gardner|Henderson|Therrien|2015|p=9}} \n\n==See also==\n* [[List of museums in Alberta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=James D.|last2=Henderson|first2=Donald M.|last3=Therrien|first3=Fran\u00e7ois|title=Introduction to the Special Issue commemorating the 30th anniversary of the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology, with a summary of the museum\u2019s early history and its research contributions|journal=Canadian Journal of Earth Science|year=2015|volume=52|issue=8|page=5\u201333|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Royal Tyrrell Museum}}\n* {{official|https://tyrrellmuseum.com}}\n\n{{portal bar|Canada|Museums|Palaeontology}}\n{{Alberta parks}}\n\n[[Category:Museums in Alberta]]\n[[Category:Natural history museums in Canada]]\n[[Category:Burgess Shale fossils]]\n[[Category:Provincial historic sites of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Canada with royal patronage]]\n[[Category:Fossil museums]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Drumheller]]\n[[Category:Dinosaur museums]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Canada]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Alberta]]\n", "name_user": "Leventio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArchitecture:cite order", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Tyrrell_Museum_of_Palaeontology"}
{"title_page": "Anita Odia", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian actress and producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Anita Odia\n| image        = Anita Caroline Odia.jpg\n| caption      = Odia in 2019\n| birth_name   = Anita Caroline Odia\n| birth_date   = February 12\n| birth_place  = [[Ikeja, Lagos]], Nigeria\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|[[Model (person)|Model]]|[[actress]]|[[film producer]]}}\n| years_active = 2012-present\n| known_for    = {{unbulleted list\n  |''[[Beauty of The Mind, (2015 film)|Beauty of The Mind]]''\n  |''[[The Silverspoon (2017 film)|The Silverspoon]]''\n  |''[[Dry Tears (2018 Nigerian film)|Dry Tears]]''\n    }}\n| awards       = [[Anita Odia#awards and recognition|See below]]\n| net_worth    = \n| website      = {{URL|akeyssproductions.com/}}\n| signature    = Anita Odia Signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Anita Caroline Odia''' is a Nigerian [[actress]] and [[Film producer|producer]] born on the 12th of February, in Lagos - Nigeria. She is the Chief Executive Officer of A. Keyss Productions,<ref>http://www.findglocal.com/NG/Gwarinpa/1690889887802566/A.-Keyss-Productions</ref> a film production company in the Federal Capital Territory, [[Abuja]] which is into making high budget Movies, Skits and Web series for the Nigerian market, such as: Beauty of The Mind, The Silverspoon and Dry Tears.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnita Caroline Odia was Born on February 12 in Ikeja, Lagos - Nigeria and she is the first of five children by a Cameroonian mother and a Nigerian father. Although born in Lagos, Anita's earliest years, including her primary education were spent in Bamenda, a city in northwestern Cameroon, before she returned to Nigeria for her Secondary School Education in Lagos and Kano states. She earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) at the [[University of Calabar]], situated in the Capital of Cross River state, a port city in southern Nigeria that shares a border with Cameroon.\n\n==Career==\n\nAnita picked up interest in acting while at the University which led her to take part in a film training workshop in Nigeria's the federal capital, [[Abuja]], in 2010, organized by the [[New York Film Academy]] in a calculated move that launched her into her acting career with a Diploma in [[acting]]. Having, prior to that registered as a member of the [[Actors Guild of Nigeria]], [[Abuja]] Chapter, she soon landed her first role in the movie, Real Wife in 2012 and by her second role in 2013 in the movie Ladies Affair, Anita's love and passion for acting and the movie industry was no longer in doubt. Subsequently (By 2014) through her \u2018A Keyss Productions\u2019, she produced her first movie; \u2018Beauty of The Mind\u2019 where she played the role of a Supporting Actress which earned 2 nominations at the International Film Festival in London (which year) as well as a nomination in 2018, for the Best Independent Film Supporting Actress in the Hollywood And African Prestigious Awards \u2013 HAPAwards, a United States of America awards which recognizes outstanding individuals whose lives have been marked by extraordinary personal and professional accomplishments.\n\n\nWith such astounding success of her first film, Anita's wade into the movie production industry, alongside acting became swifter and more sure footed as she featured in several other movies such as: From the Street, Stay with Me, Ekwueme and His Investment (in which she acted alongside the Popular Nkem Owoh and the multiple awards winning Daniel K. Daniel), Eno my Calabar Love (starring alongside Ini Edo), and Ojuko The War Lord (featured alongside Eniola Badmus and Queen Nwokoye). By 2015, under her production company, A Keyss Productions, she Co-Produced Fast Cash and then Silver Spoon and Dry Tears both of which were produced solely in 2017 and 2019 respectively.\n[[File:Anita Caroline.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Personal life==\nAnita Caroline Odia grew up in [[Bamenda]] (northwest), [[Cameroon]] where she had her my primary school education and later relocated back to Nigeria to complete her Secondary School education. She further earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) from the [[University of Calabar]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" background: #f9f9f0;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Director\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n|2012\n| ''Real Wives''<ref>https://www.nollywoodreinvented.com/2012/10/real-wives.html</ref>\n| Actress\n| Tchidi Chikere\n| With [[Stephanie Okereke]]\n|-\n|2013\n|''Ladies Affair''<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/396668679652961557/</ref><ref>https://ng.linkedin.com/in/amaechi-ukeje-b4475b53</ref>\n| Actress\n| Amechi Ukeje\n|with [[Chika Ike]], [[Funke Akindele]], [[Ebube Nwagbo]] & [[Juliet Ibrahim]]\n|-\n|2014\n|''Beauty of The Mind''<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5074428/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl</ref><ref>https://nlist.ng/title/beauty-of-the-mind-643/credits/</ref>\n| Actress, Producer\n| Okey Zebulu <ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/Beauty-Chinyere-Wilfred-Bryan-Okwara/dp/B07KMNG57L</ref>\n|with [[Nse Ikpe Etim]], [[Bryan Okwara]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2015\n|Ekwueme and His Investment <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ddBevmupr5o</ref>\n| Actress\n| Emeka Amakeze\n|with Nkem Onwo, Nichole Banna, [[Daniel K Daniel]], [[Ken Erics]]\n|-\n|Eno My Calabar Love <ref>https://g.co/kgs/PzYgTp</ref>\n| Actress\n| Emeka Amakeze\n|with [[Ini Edo]], [[Osita Iheme]], Nichole Banna\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2017\n|''Osinachi My Wife''<ref>https://nlist.ng/title/osinachi-my-wife-11772/reviews/</ref>\n|Actress\n|Chijioke Okeke\n|with Yule Edochie, Harry B\n|-\n|The Silverspoon <ref>http://onobello.com/the-silver-spoon-desmond-elliot-wole-ojo-yvonne-jedege-more-for-new-movie-watch-trailer/</ref><ref>http://thenet.ng/silver-spoon-wole-ojo-yvonne-jegede-cast-talk-new-desmond-elliot-movie/</ref>\n|Actress, Producer \n|[[Desmond Elliot]]\n|with [[Wole Ojo]], Sophie Alakija, [[Yvonne Jegede]], [[Ayo Adesanya]], Chucks Chyke\n|-\n|''Fast Cash''<ref>http://blog.irokotv.com/2016/07/07/watch-fast-cash-irokotv/</ref>\n|Actress, Co-Producer\n|Okey Zubelu\n|with [[Funnybone]], Oma Nnadi, [[Kiki Omeili]], [[Tamara Eteimo]], [[Mary Lazarus]] & Klint D Drunk\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|''From The Stress''\n|Actress\n|Tola Balogun\n|with Okey Uzoeshi, [[Ivie Okujaye]]\n|-\n|Dry Tears <ref>https://web.facebook.com/350662741803855/photos/a.355373301332799/1157246267812161/?type=1&theater</ref>\n|Actress, Producer \n|Sadiq Sule\n|with Ninolowo Bolanle, [[Bimbo Ademoye]], Ijeoma Peters\n|-\n|}\n\n==awards and recognition==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Event\n!Prize\n!Recipient \n!Result\n|-\n|2015\n|[[Zulu African Film Academy Awards]]\n|Best Actress & Best Scriptwriter\n|Beauty of The Mind\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2018\n|[[BFI London Film Festival]] - UK <ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival</ref>\n|Best Independent Film \n|Beauty of The Mind \n|{{nominated}}<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BFI_London_Film_Festival</ref><ref>https://theworldsatellite.com/2020/01/20/anita-keyss-a-testament-of-the-nollywood-dream/</ref>\n|-\n|Hollywood and African Prestigious Awards, Los Angeles\n|Best Independent Film Supporting Actress \n|Beauty of The Mind <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5074428/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl</ref>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Odia, Anita}}\n[[Category:Living people|Odia, Anita]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian actress and producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Anita Odia\n| image        = Anita Caroline Odia.jpg\n| caption      = Odia in 2019\n| birth_name   = Anita Caroline Odia\n| birth_date   = February 12\n| birth_place  = [[Ikeja, Lagos]], Nigeria\n| alma mater   = [[University of Calabar]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|[[Model (person)|Model]]|[[actress]]|[[film producer]]}}\n| years_active = 2012-present\n| known_for    = {{unbulleted list\n  |''[[Beauty of The Mind, (2015 film)|Beauty of The Mind]]''\n  |''[[The Silverspoon (2017 film)|The Silverspoon]]''\n  |''[[Dry Tears (2018 Nigerian film)|Dry Tears]]''\n    }}\n| awards       = [[Anita Odia#awards and recognition|See below]]\n| net_worth    = \n| website      = {{URL|akeyssproductions.com/}}\n| signature    = Anita Odia Signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Anita Caroline Odia''' is a Nigerian [[actress]] and [[Film producer|producer]] born on the 12th of February, in Lagos - Nigeria. She is the Chief Executive Officer of A. Keyss Productions,<ref>http://www.findglocal.com/NG/Gwarinpa/1690889887802566/A.-Keyss-Productions</ref> a film production company in the Federal Capital Territory, [[Abuja]] which is into making high budget Movies, Skits and Web series for the Nigerian market, such as: Beauty of The Mind, The Silverspoon and Dry Tears.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAnita Caroline Odia was Born on February 12 in Ikeja, Lagos - Nigeria and she is the first of five children by a Cameroonian mother and a Nigerian father. Although born in Lagos, Anita's earliest years, including her primary education were spent in Bamenda, a city in northwestern Cameroon, before she returned to Nigeria for her Secondary School Education in Lagos and Kano states. She earned a bachelor's degree in Education (B.Ed) at the [[University of Calabar]], situated in the Capital of Cross River state, a port city in southern Nigeria that shares a border with Cameroon.\n\n==Career==\n\nAnita picked up interest in acting while at the University which led her to take part in a film training workshop in Nigeria's the federal capital, [[Abuja]], in 2010, organized by the [[New York Film Academy]] in a calculated move that launched her into her acting career with a Diploma in [[acting]]. Having, prior to that registered as a member of the [[Actors Guild of Nigeria]], [[Abuja]] Chapter, she soon landed her first role in the movie, Real Wife in 2012 and by her second role in 2013 in the movie Ladies Affair, Anita's love and passion for acting and the movie industry was no longer in doubt. Subsequently (By 2014) through her \u2018A Keyss Productions\u2019, she produced her first movie; \u2018Beauty of The Mind\u2019 where she played the role of a Supporting Actress which earned 2 nominations at the International Film Festival in London (which year) as well as a nomination in 2018, for the Best Independent Film Supporting Actress in the Hollywood And African Prestigious Awards \u2013 HAPAwards, a United States of America awards which recognizes outstanding individuals whose lives have been marked by extraordinary personal and professional accomplishments.\n\n\nWith such astounding success of her first film, Anita's wade into the movie production industry, alongside acting became swifter and more sure footed as she featured in several other movies such as: From the Street, Stay with Me, Ekwueme and His Investment (in which she acted alongside the Popular Nkem Owoh and the multiple awards winning Daniel K. Daniel), Eno my Calabar Love (starring alongside Ini Edo), and Ojuko The War Lord (featured alongside Eniola Badmus and Queen Nwokoye). By 2015, under her production company, A Keyss Productions, she Co-Produced Fast Cash and then Silver Spoon and Dry Tears both of which were produced solely in 2017 and 2019 respectively.\n[[File:Anita Caroline.jpg|thumb]]\n\n==Personal life==\nAnita Caroline Odia grew up in [[Bamenda]] (northwest), [[Cameroon]] where she had her my primary school education and later relocated back to Nigeria to complete her Secondary School education.\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 100%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" background: #f9f9f0;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"back